25|$|Drivers must be 18 {{years old}} {{to qualify for a}} licence {{including}} applying for theory lessons. Once a driver passes the Basic Theory Test (BTT), a Provisional <b>Driving</b> Licence (PDL) which lasts for six months, must be applied for before taking the practical <b>driving</b> lesson. However, a student can choose to apply and pass the Final Theory Test (FTT) before applying for a PDL and starting <b>driving</b> lessons. The last stage of obtaining a <b>driving</b> licence is the practical <b>driving</b> test, for which a student must have a FTT pass result slip and a PDL.|$|E
25|$|Drunk <b>driving</b> is a {{major issue}} in New Zealand, {{especially}} among young drivers. New Zealand has relatively low penalties for drunk <b>driving.</b> In the late 2000s, reports indicated that the rate of drunk <b>driving</b> by under 20s in Auckland had risen 77% in three years, with similar increases {{in the rest of the}} country. Many drunk drivers already had convictions for previous drunk <b>driving.</b>|$|E
